1
00:06:33,880 --> 00:06:38,192
- Hang on. We're coming to a bend. - You're going too fast.

2
00:06:38,280 --> 00:06:42,796
What's this old iron doing here? I'll give you ten bob for it.

3
00:06:42,880 --> 00:06:48,273
Don't be daft. This was once a great car. It won the Grand Prix three years running.

4
00:06:48,360 --> 00:06:50,749
So it's a car, is it?

5
00:06:50,840 --> 00:06:53,149
- Certainly it's a car. - A racing car.

6
00:06:53,240 --> 00:06:55,674
- And we're winning. - You're in the way.

7
00:06:55,760 --> 00:07:00,231
You're in the way for a belt around the ear if I have any more of your lip.

8
00:07:00,320 --> 00:07:03,278
All right. I'll give you 15 bob for it.

9
00:07:03,360 --> 00:07:05,430
Make it 30 and she's yours.

10
00:07:05,520 --> 00:07:08,239
Mr Coggins, you're not going to sell her.

11
00:07:08,320 --> 00:07:12,518
Course he is. You think he's running a children's playground?

12
00:07:12,600 --> 00:07:15,398
All right, 30 bob. I'll pick her up Wednesday.

13
00:07:15,480 --> 00:07:18,278
But you promised we could play in her.

14
00:07:18,360 --> 00:07:23,434
I'm sorry, but she ain't any use to me. Times are hard.

15
00:07:23,520 --> 00:07:27,718
- But you can't take her away. - She's not any old car. She's ours.

16
00:07:27,800 --> 00:07:31,509
Not any more she ain't. I'll see you tomorrow, Bill.

17
00:07:31,600 --> 00:07:36,628
- What are you going to do with her? - We'll put her in the clapper.

18
00:07:36,720 --> 00:07:40,110
Crunch her up till she's one solid piece of metal.

19
00:07:40,200 --> 00:07:44,876
Then we're gonna put her in the furnace, melt her down till she's liquid iron.

20
00:07:44,960 --> 00:07:46,871
That's what we're gonna do.

21
00:07:48,320 --> 00:07:51,073
Look what you've done. You've frightened her.

22
00:07:51,160 --> 00:07:53,958
- She shivered. - See? She's a very special car.

23
00:07:54,040 --> 00:07:57,237
If you put her in the furnace, you'll be guilty of murder.

24
00:07:57,320 --> 00:08:01,518
And if you don't get out of it, I'll be guilty of two more murders.

25
00:08:04,760 --> 00:08:09,231
You can't sell our lovely car to that nasty man.

26
00:08:09,320 --> 00:08:13,313
I'm sorry, but I'm afraid I already have.

27
00:08:13,400 --> 00:08:16,392
I know. Daddy will buy it for us, won't he, Jemima?

28
00:08:16,480 --> 00:08:17,799
Of course.

29
00:08:17,880 --> 00:08:21,350
Promise you won't let it go until we come back.

30
00:08:21,440 --> 00:08:25,069
30 shillings, mind, not a penny less.

31
00:08:25,160 --> 00:08:27,116
- Please promise. - Please.

32
00:08:27,200 --> 00:08:30,590
- All right, I promise. - Come on, Jemima.

33
00:08:39,760 --> 00:08:42,194
That's a clever thing to do.

34
00:08:42,280 --> 00:08:45,750
- We're very sorry, miss. - I'm sure you are.

35
00:08:56,680 --> 00:09:01,390
Just look at my car. And look at the mess I'm in, too.

36
00:09:01,480 --> 00:09:06,156
- Oh, no. I think you're beautiful. - And I like your car.

37
00:09:06,240 --> 00:09:07,992
Hmm.

38
00:09:08,080 --> 00:09:11,117
You shouldn't be rushing across the road.

39
00:09:11,200 --> 00:09:15,478
You might have been killed. Anyway, why aren't you in school?

40
00:09:16,720 --> 00:09:19,109
- It isn't a holiday, is it? - No, miss.

41
00:09:20,680 --> 00:09:23,433
- Do you live around here? - Just down the road.

42
00:09:23,520 --> 00:09:26,830
Get into my car. I'm taking you home.

43
00:09:27,400 --> 00:09:31,951
Just wait till Daddy hears we've been for a ride in a motor car.

44
00:09:33,840 --> 00:09:35,990
- What's your name? - I'm Jemima.

45
00:09:36,080 --> 00:09:38,150
- And I'm Jeremy. - What's yours?

46
00:09:38,240 --> 00:09:41,277
- Truly. - That's a very pretty name.

47
00:09:41,360 --> 00:09:43,590
Now, where is your house?

48
00:09:43,680 --> 00:09:47,195
- We don't live in a house. - We live in a castle on top of a hill.

49
00:09:47,280 --> 00:09:51,068
I didn't know there were any castles around here.

50
00:09:51,160 --> 00:09:53,435
It isn't a castle exactly.

51
00:09:53,520 --> 00:09:58,548
Daddy calls it that. He says King Alfred used to live there a long time ago.

52
00:09:58,640 --> 00:10:01,154
And does your daddy know you aren't in school?

53
00:10:01,240 --> 00:10:03,356
He won't mind.

54
00:10:03,440 --> 00:10:05,431
He's awfully busy.

55
00:10:05,520 --> 00:10:09,513
Is he? Well, he'll have to find time to see me.

56
00:10:09,600 --> 00:10:12,239
I have a few things to say to him.

57
00:10:24,320 --> 00:10:27,312
Edison! Here, boy.

58
00:10:27,400 --> 00:10:29,197
Good boy.

59
00:10:29,280 --> 00:10:30,679
That's Daddy over there.

60
00:10:31,560 --> 00:10:35,917
- Hello! - Hello. You're just in time.

61
00:10:40,040 --> 00:10:43,555
- What is he up to? - That's his latest invention.

62
00:10:43,640 --> 00:10:45,631
- Rockets. - Rockets?

63
00:10:47,640 --> 00:10:50,552
Stand back. Keep clear.

64
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:54,718
Hurray!

65
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:14,834
- Does he know what he's doing? - Of course he does.

66
00:11:14,920 --> 00:11:16,433
Whoa!

67
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:38,152
That's not funny. Somebody should do something.

68
00:11:42,600 --> 00:11:44,909
Hold on.

69
00:11:45,680 --> 00:11:47,671
Wait there.

70
00:12:00,360 --> 00:12:04,239
- Thank you. - You might have gone up in flames.

71
00:12:04,320 --> 00:12:08,677
Madam, I took that into consideration. This suit is flameproof.

72
00:12:08,760 --> 00:12:12,435
- Oh, dear. - You have ruined my propulsion unit.

73
00:12:12,520 --> 00:12:15,717
- How was I to know... - Don't be cross with the lady.

74
00:12:15,800 --> 00:12:18,633
- She gave us a ride. - She was only trying to help.

75
00:12:18,720 --> 00:12:20,950
- How very kind. - Her name's Truly.

76
00:12:21,040 --> 00:12:24,032
Do you realise I nearly knocked down your children?

77
00:12:24,120 --> 00:12:26,509
We do seem to be accident-prone, don't we?

78
00:12:26,600 --> 00:12:29,034
It wasn't my fault. They came rushing...

79
00:12:29,120 --> 00:12:31,998
It was very nice of you to apologise. Tea time, children.

80
00:12:32,080 --> 00:12:34,150
- Goodbye. - Thanks for the ride.

81
00:12:34,240 --> 00:12:37,437
Don't you have something to tell your father?

82
00:12:37,520 --> 00:12:40,876
Yes, we have. Mr Coggins promised us...

83
00:12:40,960 --> 00:12:47,115
She doesn't mean about that. Daddy, we didn't go to school today.

84
00:12:47,200 --> 00:12:48,553
Oh-ho.

85
00:12:48,640 --> 00:12:52,599
It'll give the other children a chance to catch up, won't it?

86
00:12:52,680 --> 00:12:54,671
- Bye. - Bye, Truly.

87
00:12:55,280 --> 00:12:57,157
- But, Mr Potts... - Good day.

88
00:12:57,240 --> 00:13:00,232
Unstable. Definitely unstable.

89
00:13:00,320 --> 00:13:02,311
Hey, hey!

90
00:13:06,680 --> 00:13:09,114
Good afternoon, miss. Sorry I can't stop.

91
00:13:09,200 --> 00:13:13,955
I'm off to India to have tea with the maharajah. Cheerio.

92
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:51,991
Mr Potts.

93
00:13:52,600 --> 00:13:54,477
Mr Potts?

94
00:13:54,560 --> 00:13:57,233
I'm sorry to persist about this.

95
00:13:57,320 --> 00:14:01,359
Perhaps you aren't aware your children were running about in the road.

96
00:14:01,440 --> 00:14:03,112
It's not a playground...

97
00:14:03,200 --> 00:14:05,873
Would you mind pressing that switch there?

98
00:14:05,960 --> 00:14:08,394
Just behind you. On the right.

99
00:14:08,480 --> 00:14:10,471
The right?

100
00:14:11,200 --> 00:14:12,235
Thank you.

101
00:14:12,320 --> 00:14:14,914
You ought to exercise more control over them.

102
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:17,195
I suppose I could chain them up.

103
00:14:17,280 --> 00:14:20,192
On a long chain, so they get plenty of exercise.

104
00:14:20,280 --> 00:14:22,714
Don't your children go to school?

105
00:14:22,800 --> 00:14:26,031
- I have it now, you're the truant officer. - No, I'm not.

106
00:14:26,120 --> 00:14:28,429
Didn't you ever play truant?

107
00:14:28,520 --> 00:14:32,718
- I most certainly did not. - I bet you didn't.

108
00:14:33,760 --> 00:14:37,992
Would it be too much to ask what this is? This... thing?

109
00:14:38,080 --> 00:14:40,958
An invention of mine. Cleans carpets by suction.

110
00:14:41,040 --> 00:14:43,110
All that to clean carpets?

111
00:14:43,200 --> 00:14:47,876
Away with sweeping and brushing and dirty carpets.

112
00:14:52,520 --> 00:14:55,671
Is that all you do? Invent things?

113
00:14:55,760 --> 00:14:58,115
- Is that all I do? - What's this gadget?

114
00:14:58,200 --> 00:15:04,150
That's not quite right yet, but I hope to transmit moving pictures by wireless.

115
00:15:04,240 --> 00:15:06,231
- Really? - Yes, really. As Marconi...

116
00:15:06,320 --> 00:15:07,639
And this?

117
00:15:07,720 --> 00:15:11,508
This is a sweet-making machine.

118
00:15:14,400 --> 00:15:16,789
- Is this one of the sweets? - Yes, it is.

119
00:15:16,880 --> 00:15:19,519
Is it supposed to have holes in it?

120
00:15:19,600 --> 00:15:22,239
No. Actually, I think the problem...

121
00:15:22,320 --> 00:15:24,595
The boiling point of your sugar is too high.

122
00:15:24,680 --> 00:15:26,955
An expert on sweet-making, are we?

123
00:15:27,040 --> 00:15:30,715
- And an expert on child welfare. - I was only trying to help.

124
00:15:30,800 --> 00:15:35,078
Maybe my children like running wild. Did that ever occur to you?

125
00:15:35,160 --> 00:15:39,039
And how my children behave is frankly no concern of yours.

126
00:15:39,120 --> 00:15:44,194
So take off in your fancy automobile and go do good somewhere else.

127
00:15:44,280 --> 00:15:45,633
I've never been...

128
00:15:45,720 --> 00:15:48,757
Spoken to that way before? Maybe it's about time.

129
00:15:48,840 --> 00:15:51,035
Good afternoon, madam.

130
00:15:51,120 --> 00:15:53,190
Mind the cable!

131
00:15:54,800 --> 00:15:57,109
Officious, interfering...

132
00:16:06,240 --> 00:16:09,630
If women want to drive motor cars, they should learn to operate one.

133
00:16:09,720 --> 00:16:14,236
I suppose it wouldn't occur to you to offer to help me.

134
00:16:17,800 --> 00:16:20,109
Get in the car, please.

135
00:16:26,360 --> 00:16:29,033
For a mechanically-minded man...

136
00:16:29,120 --> 00:16:31,918
- Try switching it on! - Oh.

137
00:16:34,360 --> 00:16:35,759
Hmph!

138
00:16:46,640 --> 00:16:48,710
Open the throttle.

139
00:16:48,800 --> 00:16:51,394
And keep it open.

140
00:16:52,600 --> 00:16:54,079
Women!

141
00:16:58,280 --> 00:17:01,750
Confounded woman. Who does she think she is?

142
00:17:01,840 --> 00:17:05,719
Coming in here and telling me how to raise my children.

143
00:17:05,800 --> 00:17:09,554
Do I need somebody to tell me how to raise my children?

144
00:17:09,640 --> 00:17:12,632
Of course not.

145
00:17:13,680 --> 00:17:16,433
- Where's my cardigan? - Under your jacket.

146
00:17:16,520 --> 00:17:18,511
Under... Yes.

147
00:17:18,600 --> 00:17:21,398
Self-righteous busybody.

148
00:17:22,480 --> 00:17:25,438
- She won't be bothering us again. - But I liked her.

149
00:17:25,520 --> 00:17:28,353
So did I. She was very pretty.

150
00:17:28,440 --> 00:17:30,510
She certainly was.

151
00:17:31,760 --> 00:17:35,833
Do you think your father's a crackpot?

152
00:17:35,920 --> 00:17:38,673
Your cardigan's inside out.

153
00:17:39,680 --> 00:17:43,036
Do you think I'm wasting my time on silly inventions?

154
00:17:43,120 --> 00:17:45,190
But they're wonderful.

155
00:17:45,280 --> 00:17:49,671
- Nobody else could think of them. - That's right.

156
00:17:49,760 --> 00:17:52,832
Nobody else could think of them.

157
00:17:52,920 --> 00:17:56,310
After all, what makes the battle worth the fighting?

158
00:17:56,400 --> 00:17:58,595
What makes the mountain worth the climb?

159
00:17:58,680 --> 00:18:01,399
What makes the questions worth the asking?

160
00:18:01,480 --> 00:18:04,597
The reason worth the rhyme?

161
00:18:05,240 --> 00:18:08,630
## To me the answer's clear

162
00:18:08,720 --> 00:18:12,474
## It's having someone near

163
00:18:12,560 --> 00:18:14,755
## Someone dear

164
00:18:17,120 --> 00:18:21,352
## Someone to care for, to be there for

165
00:18:21,440 --> 00:18:24,432
## I have you two

166
00:18:24,520 --> 00:18:28,593
## Someone to do for, muddle through for

167
00:18:28,680 --> 00:18:31,558
## I have you two

168
00:18:31,640 --> 00:18:35,474
## Someone to share joy or despair with

169
00:18:35,560 --> 00:18:38,597
## Whichever betides you

170
00:18:38,680 --> 00:18:42,070
## Life becomes a chore

171
00:18:42,160 --> 00:18:45,675
## Unless you're living for

172
00:18:45,760 --> 00:18:49,912
## Someone to tend to, be a friend to

173
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:52,833
## I have you two

174
00:18:52,920 --> 00:18:56,833
## Someone to strive for, do or die for

175
00:18:56,920 --> 00:19:00,549
## I have you two

176
00:19:00,640 --> 00:19:06,988
## Could be we three get along so famously

177
00:19:07,080 --> 00:19:10,755
## Cos you two have me

178
00:19:10,880 --> 00:19:14,236
## And I have you two, too

179
00:19:24,080 --> 00:19:25,479
Hurray!

180
00:20:16,720 --> 00:20:17,835
Atchoo!

181
00:20:17,960 --> 00:20:21,475
## Someone to care for, to be there for

182
00:20:21,560 --> 00:20:25,030
## I have you two

183
00:20:25,120 --> 00:20:28,999
## Someone to do for, muddle through for

184
00:20:29,080 --> 00:20:32,197
## I have you two

185
00:20:32,280 --> 00:20:36,398
## Someone to smile once in a while with

186
00:20:36,480 --> 00:20:39,711
## Whenever you're lonesome

187
00:20:39,800 --> 00:20:42,917
## I've a happy lot

188
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:46,276
## Considering what I've got

189
00:20:46,360 --> 00:20:52,196
## But I couldn't do more than you do for your poor father

190
00:20:52,280 --> 00:20:53,998
Daddy!

191
00:20:54,080 --> 00:21:00,997
## Things go asunder and I wonder why you bother

192
00:21:01,640 --> 00:21:08,478
## Could be we three get along so famously cos

193
00:21:08,560 --> 00:21:11,677
## We two have you

194
00:21:11,760 --> 00:21:19,872
## And I have you two... too

195
00:21:23,960 --> 00:21:24,710
Jeremy.

196
00:21:25,480 --> 00:21:26,629
Oh, good!

197
00:21:28,520 --> 00:21:30,511
Do I smell food?

198
00:21:30,600 --> 00:21:33,114
Bring the bread, will you, Grandpa?

199
00:21:33,200 --> 00:21:36,636
- And the pepper and salt, please. - Right away, sir.

200
00:21:36,720 --> 00:21:39,757
Oh! Sausage and egg, my favourite.

201
00:21:39,840 --> 00:21:41,592
How was India?

202
00:21:41,680 --> 00:21:46,037
I got up this morning and I shot an elephant in my pyjamas.

203
00:21:46,120 --> 00:21:49,157
"How he got into my pyjamas I shall never know."

204
00:21:49,240 --> 00:21:52,118
You've heard it before.

205
00:21:59,800 --> 00:22:03,839
- I wonder how that happened. - Daddy, could we ask you something?

206
00:22:03,920 --> 00:22:08,232
- It's about Mr Coggins. - The junkman wanted to take it away.

207
00:22:08,320 --> 00:22:10,515
But Mr Coggins says if we asked you...

208
00:22:10,600 --> 00:22:13,637
- Ask me what? - He's a horrid, mean, old man.

209
00:22:13,720 --> 00:22:15,711
- Mr Coggins? - The junkman.

210
00:22:15,840 --> 00:22:18,274
He'll take it and burn it.

211
00:22:18,360 --> 00:22:20,112
What are you going on about?

212
00:22:20,200 --> 00:22:22,509
- Our car. - What about it?

213
00:22:22,600 --> 00:22:25,068
Mr Coggins is selling it to the junkman.

214
00:22:25,160 --> 00:22:28,391
And the junkman's going to put it in the furnace

215
00:22:28,480 --> 00:22:31,995
and skwodge it all up till there's nothing left.

216
00:22:32,080 --> 00:22:35,959
That's terrible. We can't let that happen, Grandpa.

217
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:38,638
No, definitely no.

218
00:22:38,720 --> 00:22:44,989
- We knew you wouldn't let him. - So we can have it for 30 shillings.

219
00:22:47,360 --> 00:22:51,512
- 30 shillings? - You can pay him tomorrow.

220
00:22:52,160 --> 00:22:55,994
Yes, well, I suppose we can work something out.

221
00:22:56,080 --> 00:22:58,036
- Good! - Hurray!

222
00:22:58,120 --> 00:23:00,680
- Are you all finished? - Yes, Daddy.

223
00:23:00,760 --> 00:23:03,354
I think you should go run up to bed.

224
00:23:03,440 --> 00:23:05,396
- Goodnight, Grandpa. - Goodnight, my boy.

225
00:23:05,480 --> 00:23:07,277
- Goodnight, Grandpa. - Goodnight, my darling.

226
00:23:07,360 --> 00:23:10,318
- Goodnight, Daddy. - Goodnight.

227
00:23:16,840 --> 00:23:20,276
You've done it now, haven't you?

228
00:23:20,360 --> 00:23:22,590
You think Coggins might do a deal?

229
00:23:22,680 --> 00:23:25,114
Him down the road? Sure.

230
00:23:25,200 --> 00:23:29,352
He's so mean he wouldn't light your pipe if his house was on fire.

231
00:23:30,760 --> 00:23:33,832
Did you hear that? You know what that means?

232
00:23:33,920 --> 00:23:36,388
I'll be up all night, rain pouring in.

233
00:23:36,480 --> 00:23:39,836
Why don't you sleep in the workshop?

234
00:23:39,920 --> 00:23:43,674
In the workshop? You promised to fix my bedroom roof.

235
00:23:43,760 --> 00:23:48,390
- I will. It's just... - Caractacus, my boy. Listen...

236
00:23:48,480 --> 00:23:50,471
It's time you woke up.

237
00:23:50,560 --> 00:23:54,269
- At your age, I did a day's work... - For a day's pay, polishing boots.

238
00:23:54,360 --> 00:23:56,430
I was the smartest batman in the army.

239
00:23:56,520 --> 00:24:01,150
When my brigadier went into action, the natives were so blinded by his boots,

240
00:24:01,240 --> 00:24:04,789
they couldn't see to fight.

241
00:24:10,440 --> 00:24:13,750
Catch me death of cold. He don't care.

242
00:24:13,840 --> 00:24:16,877
Nobody cares. Me own son.

243
00:24:39,520 --> 00:24:42,671
She was right. Who wants sweets with holes in them?

244
00:24:52,120 --> 00:24:55,112
Edison, stop that whistling.

245
00:25:00,440 --> 00:25:03,591
Edison, do that again.

246
00:25:10,840 --> 00:25:15,391
Edison, you're a genius.

247
00:25:27,280 --> 00:25:31,273
The employment office is in the rear.

248
00:25:32,480 --> 00:25:35,552
You see, I've invented these sweets.

249
00:25:35,640 --> 00:25:38,438
Really? Name?

